Our evaluation of CPU utilization patterns across Hyperledger Fabric versions 2.1 through 2.4 and our optimized implementation reveals significant efficiency improvements in blockchain operations for immigration management. Under standardized workload conditions (500 TPS of 2KB transactions), Fabric 2.1 exhibited the highest CPU demand at 78.4% average utilization across all peers, with frequent spikes to 92% during state validation. Subsequent versions showed incremental gains, with Fabric 2.4 reducing average CPU usage to 65.2% through improved parallel transaction processing. Our modified version achieves a dramatic 41.8% reduction in CPU overhead compared to Fabric 2.4, maintaining just 38.1% average utilization while processing 1.2× more transactions. This efficiency stems from three key optimizations: (1) a streamlined PBFT message path that reduces cryptographic verification cycles by 37%, (2) batched state updates that decrease I/O wait times, and (3) our custom resource governor that dynamically throttles non-critical operations during peak loads. The thermal throttling incidents observed in Fabric 2.1-2.3 (occurring every 8.2 minutes on average) were completely eliminated in our implementation, enabling sustained operation at 1,200 TPS without exceeding \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
